segments.text: Okay, well good morning everybody.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Thank you so much for joining us.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: It's a beautiful morning, if cold.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: I'm Tammy Morales, Seattle City Council member from District 2.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: District 2 includes Georgetown and Soto, so I'm really happy to be here this morning.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: I'm here because I'm announcing that my office has secured a million dollars in funding.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: to sustain the Seattle Maritime Academy's operations for the 2022-2023 school year.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: This will maintain critical technical maritime education in Seattle, education that serves as a pipeline for the maritime industry, whether we're talking about our Washington State Ferry System, our Coast Guard, our fishing fleet,
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: $750,000 of the million will provide gap funding to Seattle colleges for the operation of the Seattle Maritime Academy.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: The remaining will be allocated for community outreach and recruitment through the Maritime Academy's partnership with Seattle Public Schools and their Maritime Vessel Operations Program.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: These programs provide the classroom instruction and the hands-on training on working vessels that really help our young people prepare for a career in the maritime industry, which we all know is really important to our region's exporters.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: For example, our agricultural industry relies on our ports.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: So these are really important jobs and important programs to help our young people get the training they need to participate.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: And what's important is that it's also about increasing access for low-income families, for young people who don't have access to some of the other programs.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: These are for folks who have the opportunity now for really high-paying, skilled union work.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: And these are jobs that offer stable employment and really great career pathways.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: So I'm excited to be able to offer this GAP funding, but I can't take all the credit.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: This was a collaborative effort made possible by many people.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: So I want to thank Governor Inslee.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: I want to thank Stephanie Bowman, who is the new Maritime Industry Sector Lead at the Department of Commerce, John Persak from the Office of Economic Development, and Mayor Harrell, who supported the use of funds in this way.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: And finally, I want to say thank you to Chancellor Pan and to Dan Gullisman for your work to create economic opportunities for our young people.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: I want to say a special thank you to the young people of Seattle.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: For the last two years, they've really struggled through so much uncertainty in their schools, in their community.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Our young people have really had to navigate some extraordinary circumstances.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: So I'm hopeful that our young people will take advantage of the opportunity to attend the Maritime Academy and to train for some very high-paying jobs that really offer financial security for them.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: And now I want to invite some representatives who were all part of the collaborative effort to make this happen.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Next, we will hear from Kendi Yamaguchi, Deputy Mayor from the Mayor's Office.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: We'll hear from John Lederer, who's the Director of Key Industries and Workforce Development for the Office of Economic Development.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Louise Charon, who's the Chair of the Board of Trustees for Seattle Colleges.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Daniel Gollisman, who's the principal of the Seattle Skills Center with Seattle Public Schools.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Barrett Erickson, who is the Director of Workforce Development for the Sailors Union of the Pacific.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: And Forrest Reese, who is a student at the Seattle Maritime Academy.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: So I'm gonna hand it over to Deputy Mayor Yamaguchi.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Thanks for being here, everyone.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_04

segments.text: Great.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_02

segments.text: Good morning.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_02

segments.text: And on behalf of Mayor Bruce Harrell, I am pleased to join you today as we come together to actually celebrate this investment to our local maritime industry.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_02

segments.text: And I want to acknowledge Councilmember Morales and all of the work that she has done around this issue as well.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_02

segments.text: So Seattle is known for maritime and for well over a century Ballard has served as a center of our local maritime industry and our Seattle colleges have played a key role in providing education and training pathways at the Seattle Maritime Academy.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_02

segments.text: The Academy supports workforce training for operations in our waterways, vessel operations at our fish and urns terminal, and our Washington state ferries, which you might catch a few glimpses outside.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_02

segments.text: The Academy serves a critical role in making sure new and qualified people enter our workforce and enjoy middle and high wage
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_02

segments.text: earning careers, and it provides the necessary job training to backfill our current staffing and crew shortages and creates career opportunities to ensure we have jobs that are accessible and inclusive for all.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_02

segments.text: Through this key partnership with the City of Seattle, the State of Washington, acknowledging the Governor as well, the Seattle Maritime Academy, Seattle Public Schools Skills Center,
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_02

segments.text: and others, we celebrate this milestone that addresses the immediate threat of the Maritime Academy closing and helps the industry recover from our pandemic, as well as supporting the hiring of newly trained and diverse young talent.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_02

segments.text: So we want to thank everybody for joining us today.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_02

segments.text: And we know that this is the beginning of more work to ensure sustainable support
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_02

segments.text: for this industry, and we again celebrate this investment to keep the doors open for our young people and our community.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_02

segments.text: Thank you.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_02

segments.text: Thank you, Deputy Mayor Yamaguchi, and good morning, everybody.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: It's great to be here as a city family and with our partners as we celebrate this strategic investment that supports the future of the maritime industry.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: I'm John Lederer.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: I'm manager for key industries and workforce development at the Office of Economic Development and I'm glad to be here in interim director Markham McIntyre's absence this morning.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: The Seattle Office of Economic Development is using economic recovery dollars to help solve a dilemma at the Seattle Maritime Academy.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: This funding will support one of our
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: local key industries that provide Seattle workers with an accessible pathway to rewarding careers in the maritime industry.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: A portion of the funds will be made available to the Seattle Maritime Academy to support maritime career and technical education pathways.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: They will partner with the Seattle Public Schools Skills Center to strengthen community outreach and expand youth
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: the youth pipeline into these rewarding maritime occupations.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Now, if we're honest, Washington's maritime labor force lacks sufficient diversity at all operational levels.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: It's less racially diverse than both the maritime industry in the United States overall and the rest of the Pacific Coast.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: And it doesn't yet reflect, most importantly, the full diversity of our Seattle area communities.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: This investment and a commitment to equitable outreach and community engagement will help us begin to address these disparities by focusing our recruitment efforts within Seattle's Black, Indigenous, and other communities of color.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: We recognize that more effort is needed to sustain this training pathway going forward, and the Office of Economic Development will continue to support
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: the Seattle Colleges, elected officials, and the governor's office to develop a plan for the long-term sustainability of the Seattle Maritime Academy and the industry as a whole.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: And finally, I want to echo some of Councilmember Morales' remarks and call out the extraordinary effort
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: of really two key people that helped get us to this point today.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: John Persak, who works with me on the key industries team, is the Maritime Manufacturing and Logistics Strategic Advisor at Seattle OED, and also Stephanie Bowman, Governor Inslee's Maritime Sector Lead at the Washington Department of Commerce.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: I want to thank you both for your hard work, your strategic thinking, and your commitment
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: to this incredibly important industry that helps make Seattle who we are.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: So I want to thank you all for being here today and I also want to invite Louise Chernin for her remarks.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: She's the chair of the board of trustees at the Seattle Colleges.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_00

segments.text: Good morning, everybody.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: Workforce development.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: Interesting, I think.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: We throw that word around a lot, that phrase around a lot, but it has never been more apparent since the pandemic how absolutely essential workforce development is to provide living wage jobs and address income inequality.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: I'm very proud to be associated with Seattle Colleges and one of our most important programs
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: the Seattle Maritime Academy, which was in danger of closing just recently, just this last week or two.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: It really took, first of all, Stephanie Bowman.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: I want to thank her so much for her tenacity, for her passion.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: For Workforce Development and the Maritime Academy, I want to thank the Mayor, Deputy Mayor Yamaguchi, who's here with us today, and Council Member Tammy Morales, for understanding that if we're really going to provide living wage jobs, if we're really serious about ensuring that our students of color, that our LGBTIQ students, our immigrant students, our first-generation students,
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: have access to good jobs, then we have to support workforce development.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: We have to ensure that we have access to these programs.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: And this program provides some of the best wage jobs you can have.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: But what we really learned in the last two weeks is this program is loved.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: It is so loved by our community.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: I cannot tell you the hundreds, probably thousands of letters we have received from community members
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: all over the country, all over the United States, saying do not close these programs.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: They are unique.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: We also learned they're not only just loved by the students and by the community, but they're essential for the economy.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: The Seattle Maritime Academy is the only training academy in our region to provide these jobs for our maritime industry.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: We're surrounded by water.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: We need
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: good, skilled maritime workers, and there's only one place that provides that.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: But we have not invested appropriately in any of our workforce development, and I think we've had this wake-up call.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: And I'm so proud that for the first time, I believe we really are all on the same page, that it takes community, it will take industry, private industry, and it will take government to work together to do outreach, to ensure that we have
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: the word out about these amazing programs and that we support them.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: We support them in new ways because we understand how essential they are to change the dynamic for those who are often left out of finding opportunities that they can succeed in and that provides the skilled workers.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: I mean, for those of us who depend on ferries, we know the crisis we are in in the Northwest and specifically in Seattle.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: This is the academy that
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: that provides the skills and education for those workers.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: So I believe we not just found today this amazing million dollars from the City of Seattle, but that we are starting to look at what does it mean to be sustainable?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: How do we fund the programs that are needed to provide opportunity and address worker shortage and ensure everyone gets living wage jobs?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: So I believe it's a new day.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: We have a lot of work to make sure this program is sustainable.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: I think we're ready to roll up our sleeves, and I think we're ready to work together as one, as industry, government, and community comes together.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: And on behalf of Seattle Colleges, I think it's a great start today, and I cannot be more proud to be with a group of people committed to our students' education and to this important industry.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: So, thank you all so much.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: Today is a hopeful day for the Seattle Maritime Academy.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: Thank you.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_06

segments.text: Good morning.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I'm Dan Golisman principal of the Seattle Skills Center.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: On behalf of Seattle Public Schools I want to thank council member council member Morales Stephanie Bowman from Governor Inslee's team and John Persak from the Office of Economic Development of the city of Seattle for their work to help raise awareness about the maritime college and career opportunities for the youth of Seattle.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: The Seattle Skills Center has a wide range of amazing career and technical education programs for Seattle's high school students, including our Maritime Vessel Operations program.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: This funding will help us spread the word to students and families about the high-wage, high-demand career opportunities in maritime, and will be especially helpful in recruiting women and students of color furthest from educational justice who have historically been underrepresented in this career pathway.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: When I think about the kind of engagement work we want to do with these funds and the type of recruitment, I think of students like Manny.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I remember in the first couple of weeks of our Maritime Vessel Operations class, while the students were learning to sail, he was hesitant to go out solo in the boat.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: This was a new experience for Manny.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: This was a couple of years ago.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: He was one of our students about two years ago.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: He handled the lines and watched and learned and eventually steered and worked his way to sailing solo and taking the helm.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: He graduated a couple of years ago from the Skills Center and is now a confident young man attending the Seattle Maritime Academy, ready to start out his career in the maritime industry.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: This funding will help me be able to tell more stories like Manny's.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Students who join us at the Skills Center will be well prepared for the Seattle Maritime Academy.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And by using the Seattle Promise Scholarship, they will complete the program and start their careers debt free.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: We look forward to continuing to work with our partners at the Seattle Maritime Academy, as well as our many other partners, like the Port of Seattle, Washington State Ferries, Youth Maritime Collaborative, Sound Experience, Center for Wooden Boats, the Manufacturing Industrial Council, our labor partners, and many more.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Thank you again on behalf of the Seattle Skills Center and Seattle Public Schools.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Good morning.
